node.text: Tracking snaks with Pınar! 🤣 Here we notice the ridges and direction of travel in this lateral undulating trail of a snake. Lateral undulation is a very common form of snake locomotion, but there are several other gaits snakes can use! For further reference check out “Tracks & Signs of Reptiles and Amphibians” by Filip Tkaczyk

node.text: Tracking snaks with Pınar! 🤣 Here we notice the ridges and direction of travel in this lateral undulating trail of a snake. Lateral undulation is a very common form of snake locomotion, but there are several other gaits snakes can use! For further reference check out “Tracks & Signs of Reptiles and Amphibians” by Filip Tkaczyk

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Pınar & So on July 10, 2021.

node.text:
For me, so much of tracking is about the aesthetic beauty of traces of animacy. It’s not just about answers. It’s not about this = equals = this, because I think that can really obscure the process of getting there, which is so often a humbling process of getting to know a place, and non-human persons within it. Often it takes me weeks or even months to figure out why or how a track or sign was made, or by whom. Sharing it here is about the experience of seeing. It's easy to get caught up in identifying before we’re ready to, in some of the worlds we walk in.
__
There are many memorable times I’ve seen a track or sign that I thought I recognized, and rushed into an incorrect assumption about the identity of the track-maker. It happens a lot, especially when I see something that looks familiar, but upon closer inspection, is not quite what I thought it was. It often happens when I don’t take the time to look close enough and question my assumptions which is (supposed to be) a big part of tracking (medicine, science, etc…) but in practice, we often slip into assumptions, because it’s cognitively easier than taking in/orienting to new information. 
__
Our minds evolved to take cognitive shortcuts because a lot of the time they help. Some people who study the psychology of decision making call these  “heuristics.” But some of the time heuristics lead us to the wrong answers, as do assumptions. AND as people who walk with varying bodies of experience in the world, we have to utilize certain heuristics/assumptions a lot because they keep us safe. 
__
It’s a constant practice to disrupt/interrupt certain heuristic programs that I am running in my nervous system.
I don’t track because I’m curious all the time. That’s not how it works. I don’t feel safe enough to be curious all the time. I also track to disrupt inertia, and to counter the tide of disenchantment that lives, not just in institutions, but in colonized aspects of my own psyche. Tracks, and bodies, are always iterations, never copies: there are always new stories being told. (Photo: perfect Bighorn Sheep tracks, easily confused with deer)

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Pınar & So on June 15, 2021. May be an image of 2 people, tree and outdoors.

node.text:
Most Things Leave a Trace. This is the premise of Tracking, the oldest science. This is really more spellwork than critique, but we are able to believe it’s possible to Leave No Trace because of a deanimated view of the world that was/is imposed upon us. Obviously, we can still refrain from littering, we can reduce our impact, and practice awareness of the traces we do leave, while still believing in the inevitability of Traces; participating in that animistic revival. Countertracking (covering one’s tracks) is an ancestral art of resistance, too, and is an example of how an intimacy with Traces means that we sometimes devote a lot of focus to concealing (though never really erasing) them.
__
Tracking is a way of seeing that anticipates animacy everywhere by looking for its effects on matter. This includes the scuff of paw on dirt, but also extends to the low hanging branch sweeping a crescent on the ground below as the wind blows, the seaweed and driftwood etching a water line across the beach.  Rare is the surface or substrate that is free from traces of the animate. 
__
Many of us tune out traces of the animate as sensory background noise. The labyrinthine beetle galleries are just part of our mental search image for “log.” They are not named, not introduced to us, unless perhaps we become entomologists. The pushed-down grass in the meadow from where the deer bedded down at night are ‘just part of how meadows look.’ But Life braids around us, skirts around the edges of our awareness, plays hide and seek in the shadows of our sensory fields. In the practice of becoming more aware of these ghostly passages that occur when I’m not looking (because that’s when 90% of global or local events occur, though various media tricks us into thinking otherwise) I notice that life becomes more full of something; Mystery.
((CONTINUED IN COMMENTS))
📸 by @pattiegonia

node.text:
Performing human is my drag.

There is a network of underground rivers beneath our feet as well as beneath our skin. These whispering aquifers are roadmaps to Indigenous multi-species futurities.

When you travel down these luminescent streams, you will come across underwater tracks of (y)our ancestors. This is where Blood Memory lives… in the rich marrow of Pachamama. This is where we find refuge and shared presence across time and space.

When I speak to lifeform-queer, I am not talking about post-human genders.
That isn’t what Indigenous prismatic magic points to.

Our genders are the smell of sun-kissed willows.
Our pronouns are the descending Canyon Wren notes mirroring the bubbling waters of a spring.
Descending since we know that what is Holy lies beneath the soil.

We are not only expressions of our lands — we are in murmuration with our lands and our transcestors.
Tricksters are our cousins who we have inside jokes with.
Shapeshifting is our mother tongue.
Our kink lives where land speaks.

We have never lost our connection like they want us to believe.
Our ecological kin look with double-eyes at us — affirming our medicine and calling us forth.

I bare my green gills wrapped around my torso as a response and prayer to this accountability.

You are ready.
We are ready.

Let us be fluid + steadfast, darlings.

node.text:
Our friend Filip Tkaczyk is an incredible naturalist, photographer, ecophilosopher, and is also the author of “Tracks and Signs of Reptiles and Amphibians,” which is the only tracking field guide in its category. We wanted to give him a platform to share about one of his favorite animals, and one whom we want to learn more about: Rattlesnakes! Now is the time of year where human and rattlesnake encounters are increasing here in the semi deserts of eastern Washington. We have been rattled at a couple of times recently and were grateful for the warning: they are very camouflage and can be seen (or not seen) sunning themselves on trails. However, we are not their prey and they seek to avoid conflict if at all possible. Moving slowly while in rattlesnake territory is a great way to avoid startling them!
—
“Rattlesnakes are one of the most misunderstood wild beings. They are in truth, incredibly shy, generally unobtrusive wild relatives. I find their beauty stunning. Recently I ran a weekend program where I brought a class of 6 adult students out into the sagebrush steppe and they got to experience Northern Pacific Rattlesnakes (pictured here) up close and in the wild. 
—
For several students, this was their first encounter. I got to demonstrate how these snakes really just want to back away and hide when faced with potential danger. We saw 4 and most of them did not so much as rattle, but instead retreated immediately under the nearest protective cover. Rattlesnakes are intimately tactile, seeking contact with others of their own species. They have preferred friends they like to hang out with. They are caring mothers, some species stay with their young until the babies—which are born live, not from eggs—have had their first meal or first shed. A vast majority of rattlesnake bites are considered “dry” and fewer than 10 people a year die due to complications from bites in the USA. They are sacred beings, reminding us to have respect and that some wild beings are too sacred to be touched. Admire them with your eyes, ears, and heart!”
—
⚡️Always seem medical care if you are bitten (see comments)⚡️How are snakes special to you personally or culturally? 🐍

node.text:
WHEN CYBERPUNKS BECAME ECOLOGISTS
—
The effects of many of us millennials particularly life scientists/naturalists/environmentalists reaching adulthood who grew up during the dawn of the World Wide Web, and furthermore, the older Gen X legacies of hacker culture and gaming console culture, is really interesting. I haven't seen this represented much in pop culture in a way that isn’t ethically dogmatic, as it seems so many are still working through the problems bestowed upon us by the splitting of nature/culture, artificial/natural, etc. To bring some of this aesthetic, somatic, and intellectual lineage into the light, I wanted to share my poem about "Coming of Age in Cyberspace” written a few years ago.

"I grew up in an unfurling wilderness 
of interconnected machines
—the 90’s.
No one taught me to hunt deer
so I hunted for modems,
memorized the tones of
analog phones
instead of bird song.
Carrier signals
were like the calls of rare
and elusive
creatures
obscured by a vegetation of wire.
IP addresses
glowed on screens
like footprints
winding through terminals of text,
laying trails
that could be followed.
.
No one taught us to dream with the earth
or be possessed by the spirits
of the animals,
so I was haunted
by the strange wildness
of networks.
A virtual ecology
with its own terrain
yet animated by that original pump,
the heart.
In a queer/dystopian mythos
the disembodied soul
was the animal I hunted,
the one whose movements
I longed to understand.
.
Eventually, after years
of tracing circuits
with my finger
as braille
—the promise of meaning
looming in the dark—
I found a path
leading back
(or maybe forward?)
into the “eco”system
a green world
of soft borders
and furry logic.
.
Trailing a deer
in desert twilight
we became spirits
chasing the horizon
like a dream.
Cloven tracks glow darkly
on the sand,
their magnetism
like the static fuzz 
of those glass screens
that flooded the bedroom
of my youth
with foreign light.
The medium
has changed
but the potent dazzle
of mystery
is the same,
and the green-tinged window
to the Other-world
remains.
.
it was a network
of machines
that taught me
relationship is the
magical substance
of our world."

Ecology and animism are two facets of the same thing for us. One is a study of place-based relationships, the other is a felt experience of them. Furthermore, non-human animals also have their own ways of studying relationships, ‘ecology,’ and have their own ways of experiencing aliveness and otherness in the world. Following their trails, seeing how they ‘mark’ the land intentionally, it’s impossible to deny that they read the landscape too and they also anticipate the mystery of the alive world, in their own way. 
__
Ecology and animism have been artificially separated within settler science. But sciences are starting to become reanimated! Lots of folks are coming out of this closet. 🥳 Enchanted ecologists, bedazzled biologists, soulful soil scientists, oh yes!
__
A psycho-spiritual pillar of the project of queer nature-connection, for us, is about reaching for truly interpersonal (reciprocal , emotional, respectful) relationships with other species, with place, with natural systems & forces. An endeavor that we don’t claim authority on, nor anywhere near mastery, god no. We are interested in this apprenticeship and that’s part of why we do this! Humility and a healthy relationship with unknowing (though NOT willful ignorance or closed-mindedness) is a vital part of both spirituality and science. 
__
We find ourselves in a strange window in history, especially in settler society where we live in a condition of “species isolation." Environments that we often find ourselves in are not very (perceptibly) populated by the voices and presences of other species—when there are other species around in human habitats, it’s often a monoculture or many of one kind. Even though there are of course thousands of unseen microorganisms with us all the time, most of us did not grow up with stories that might honor these beings ( @microanimism )💚. This impacts (and shapes) our identities, and even our concepts of identity, in ways we might not fully know!
__
A diverse array of cross-species attachments are part of normative human emotional worlds. There’s not necessarily anything supernatural about this. And whatever mystery is out there, we already belong to it.

Gender as the Shape of Our Relationality // Gender seems about so much more than identity, or even so much “less” depending on how you want to look at it—even though somatic being is not lesser than ideas about it. What many of us call gender feels like it can be so related to place. A watershed, a confluence of place, culture/race/ethnicity, animistic relations/hauntings, sovereignty...

I think gender and personhood are very closely coupled. In fact, I don’t know if they are really separate things. It feels confusing that they’ve been so separated in settler ideologies. In the feminist deconstructionist framework that we came of age in, people shied away from the oppressive specter of “roles” and gravitated towards “identity.” For good reason.

But that all left us wanting a kind of role. Left us dreaming of queer monasteries and punk shepherds. I don’t want to be the only one to figure out who I am. I want the land to tell me too. The stars, the deer.
—
Maybe some in Euro-centric worlds worry that to conflate gender with place, land, even soul is to depoliticize it. Yet place, land is the ground of (cosmo-)politics!

When I think of what gender is to me, I think about  a few key elements. One is Eros (more-than-human & not sex-centric). Eros is about the human-inclusive animal, plant, fungal, and even molecular desire inherent in the cosmos to connect with Other and Self simultaneously, to connect and transform, evolve and decompose. Relationality, kinship, & signification/biosemiotics, feel like related key elements too.

This is to say concepts of Eros and desire have been far too sexualized and human-centered in some circles. We make ourselves into symbols and we signify things to Others. Not just human others, but beyond-human Others (this is a core aspect of mystical ascetic traditions). The body as beacon, message, apocalyptic vehicle, as blinking neon sign to the sacred or to something beyond ourselves. Our body as story, gender as not so much about identity and ideas but gender as dance.
Body as habitus. (CONTINUED IN COMMENTS)
